</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uorionxvi.showPublicProfile?language=EN>OrionXVI</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/14/02 5:43:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgroverants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=650.topic&index=706>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Conversation: What about Us! (State of The Druid)</span><hr size=1> The problem that both cleric and druid classes seem to be having is the lesser need for heals in XP groups.  Clerics moan constently about maintaining the edge for them in groups because they can't level without them.  Therefore, they have to find a place in a group, even if that means bumping out other classes, or not level at all.<br>
<br>
That does leave raids, which is where the cleric still shines, and most probably believe that they should, beacues it is a rard road to go down.<br>
<br>
So, the catch with your new heal is this:  if you can heal as well as a similar cleric, they won't be (for the most part) leveled anymore.  I've heard the argument that clerics still have rez, but that now entails is needing one per zone, as apposed to one per group.  So, while the cleric is left out on experience groups, they'll still ask for rezzes.  Maybe it's not right, but that's what will end up happening.<br>
<br>
So, the question still remains.  What can you do to add to druids to make them more raid friendly?  Well, the best guess would place it into getting something that shows your utility, but doesn't infringe on other classes.<br>
<br>
Just my 2¢.<br>
